ctor-network theory ­- an approach common in studies of science and management but seldom applied in this field - it offers readers an inside view into elite sport and the part that technology plays in training, competition and broadcasting. Sport and technology offers theoretical insights relevant to students and scholars of sport and sociology. It will also be fascinating reading for anyone interested in elite sporting practice in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aScience (General). 0aSociology (General). 0aSports. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / General.2bisacsh  aAnnemarie Mol.  aBruno Latour.  aElite sport.  aJohn Law.  aMichele Callon.  aSport performance.  aSport science.  aTechnology.1 aKerr, Roslyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781784995201zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784995201zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784995201/original  a978-3-11-128282-4 Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA